commText: B0$ When you come to Bangalore, you know it's a good wicket. Early part of IPL you get a lot of dew. You want to start well and then alter whatever is there in your mind. It was slightly tacky to start off. It's important to go through that and then look to accelerate. We kept it simple and tried to get as much as possible in the second half of the game. (On Dube) He is someone who can hit very cleanly. He has an issue with the fast bowlers but he's a clean hitter against the spinners. We had certain plans for him but once he arrived for our camp, he was injured. So we couldn't do a lot of work. We feel that he's somebody who can deliver and who can get those extra runs in the middle overs. He needs to believe in that more than us. We know he has the talent, but once you cross the boundary ropes into the field you are on your own. Whenever you score 220, the batsmen need to keep on hitting. If Faf and Maxi had continued, they would have won it by the 18th over. I keep assessing from behind the wicket, I am always involved in what needs to be done rather than thinking about the result. (Death overs) It is a difficult one for the youngsters, specially at this time of the year with the dew around. But they are working hard. Bravo is one of the specialists. Under him, the bowlers will gain confidence. It's a team game. The coach, the bowling coach and the senior players guide them.

B0$ We all know when we play in Bangalore it will be a good pitch with small boundaries, we have to embrace that. I stuck to the plans and was able to execute them. Today, one side was big and the other was really small. So trying to keep the batters score to the bigger side was the plan. MS just said to the bowlers we’ve spoken a lot about our plans, now it is about execution. I’m a big believer of staying in the present. In T20 cricket, even if one over comes here and there, I have three more overs to come back and make an impact. I just try to stay in the moment and keep the belief in myself.

B0$ Early on in the match, I was diving around and I thought I went at it with my rib, that was the cause of discomfort. I think we played it perfectly, the last five overs were set up for the finish. DK finishing the game, that's bread and butter for him, but that shows how good their bowling was. 200 was going to be par, we went for few runs towards the end. We could have minimised the damage by restricting them (for less than 20 in an over.) The last four overs was where it was set up for a perfect finish. It was one of those wickets, one of the best (for batters.) As a bowler you need to be skilful, Siraj was unbelievable. We couldn't manage to finish it off, but we got to move on. I lost a little bit of power towards the end, was disappointed as I got stiff. Need to keep going harder against the spinners in the middle overs.

A magnificent 83 from Conway, 24-ball fifty from Dube and cameos from Rahane, Rayudu and Moeen powered CSK to 226 - the second highest total of the season. In reply, the hosts lost two wickets in two overs with CSK's Impact Player nipping out Kohli in the very first over. At 15/2, Faf du Plessis was joined by Maxwell and the two overseas RCB batters decided to take the attack to the CSK bowlers. It was carnage from both ends. It didn't matter who was bowling, the match-ups were ridiculed as Maxwell and Faf forged a 126-run stand for the third wicket. With 86 needed off 8 overs, the game was in the balance and that's when Theekshana provided the crucial breakthrough by inducing a false stroke from Maxi. Du Plessis, dropped on 0 and 52, followed him in the very next over as he fell to Moeen. Pathirana and Deshpande were summoned to bowl in the death overs and they delivered under pressure. They bowled a few wides, but MSD would be pretty pleased with that performance as they held their nerves. Stick around for the presentations...

B0$ That's a massive total posted by Chennai Super Kings after put in to bat first. They lost Gaikwad early, but there was no looking back after that. Rahane attacked them right from the word go, and got the momentum back in CSK's favour. Conway didn't waste any time either as he looked in sublime touch right from the start of the match. Along with Rahane he had a lovely partnership, and once Rahane departed, it was Dube who joined the act. Dube hit few of the biggest sixes of the evening, as he notched up a brisk fifty. Conway had a chance to notch up a century, but Harshal Patel got him out with a yorker. Moeen and Jadeja struck a few lusty blows towards the end, and helped CSK post the second highest total of the season. Vijaykumar Vyshak who had an impressive IPL debut had a forgetful night. He went for 62 runs off 4 overs, but Rayudu's wicket might have given him some respite. The other RCB bowlers were punished too, so it wasn't a great outing for them overall. Plenty of batters in RCB dugout, but will they be able to overcome the challenge. Looks difficult, but not impossible! Back in 10 minutes for the second essay..

Less than an hour after the final ball was bowled on a cheery Saturday evening at the Chinnaswamy Stadium, the glow of victory had already given way to the next thing. Scores of supporters queued up on Queens Road seeking tickets for Monday night's blockbuster. 
 
By Thursday evening, the messaging from the Royal Challengers Bangalore management, at the venue and on social media, was that the game against Chennai Super Kings was sold out. And still supporters from as far away as Belagavi, Hubli and from Dharmapuri on the other side of the state border held out hope, forcing willing passerbys into conversation in the hope of receiving some intel. This frenzy had been foreseen and tickets priced differentially higher to the other games here. Even so, on the black market, there are takers willing to spend six times the face value of an already-inflated price for a ticket. 
 
All of this to be a part of a heaving melange of red and yellow and witness Virat Kohli and MS Dhoni share a cricket field together. These two sides have played 30 times but the 31st is heightened by the possibility of it being this pair's last meeting as two active cricketers. There is no return leg at Chepauk and certainly no guarantee of both sides qualifying to the Playoffs. This potential last dance, of course, is an assumption. Dhoni has 'definitely not' confirmed any rumours of this being a farewell season but his persistent knee trouble and those wild, final-over finishes have brought a valedictory feel to every CSK game. 
 
All of this narrative building, the socio-political and cultural context to an IPL game is on the outside. Inside, Kohli, Dhoni and their teams inhabit a world dominated by the jargon of 'good areas' and 'processes', one of more theory and lesser drama. Several column inches have been dedicated in the past as to how different these two are and how their teams have been an extension of their personality. But they've found common ground over the years in their ability to pace themselves, to harness their physical and emotional resources, to pare and slice away anything extraneous until only what is most essential remains. And so, at stake tomorrow are two points, the exact same number available in any other league game. They will take one of these two sides a little away from the early season mid-table funk.
